Since light absorption in naphthalimides with D–π–A architecture generates charge transfer interactions between the carbonyl groups and the substituents at the C-4 position, their photophysical characteristics are mainly connected to the polarization of the chromophoric system.25,26 The absorption spectrum of BHSHNI in DMSO (1 × 10–4 M) presented in Fig. S5A suggested two absorptions at 342 and 391 nm for π–π* and n–π* transitions.27,28 The Tauc plot (Fig. S5B) with energy versus αhν1/2 was used to estimate the optical band gap of BHSHNI, which was found to be 2.87 eV. The molar extinction coefficient (ε), which defines the amount of light absorbed by BHSHNI was calculated using Eq. 1.1ε=A/mC\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
